This burdened proscriptions lead women either to 1. suffer through illegal approaches preventing several unsafe abortions attempting to end unwanted pregnancies, 2. endure restraining living conditions with little to no feasible hopes for welfare, health and fulfillment and 3. fulfill miscarriages. Abortion is high in the country due to a difficult pregnancy and childbirth caused by socio-ecological conditions. This extends to the point of endangerment and detriment to women’s health, lives and families in addition to political implications in the country due to the restrictive health care for women. In accordance with law, abortion is framed here as a panacea with lacking educational opportunities and ban against foreign-trained medical professionals, where women throughout Yemen through these methods face, aimlessly, high maternal mortality.

If a woman remains pregnant following rape or incest, “it is possible that the pregnancy is permitted to continue, and it may still be possible to induce an abortion after a special court has ordered it.” The exceptions for abortion in the Yemeni penal code, however, lie only within rape and incest. “The terms “rape” and “incest” are not defined by the Penal Law. However a court may use any position it considers in the conduct of proceedings, and therefore in Yemen it is understandable that the interpretation is less stringent than in countries with a similar penal code.” In analyzing these rights, several cases exist whereby women are denied these implicit rights:
